  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3874028516" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3874028516" />
    <a title="Mash" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/121198397-mash"><img alt="Mash" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1617555915p2/121198397.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3874028516?book_show_action=true">Apr 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mash" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mash" href="/user/show/121198397-mash">Mash</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121198397-mash?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121198397-mash?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121198397-mash?shelf=may-2021-tbr">may-2021-tbr</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121198397-mash?shelf=read-in-2021">read-in-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121198397-mash?shelf=dark-but-really-good">dark-but-really-good</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121198397-mash?shelf=buddy-reads">buddy-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3874028516" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9753148720196838150">*.·:·.☽✧ <b>5 stars</b> ✧☾.·:·.*<br/><br/><i>~Buddy-read with my favourite demon AKA <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/75966379-lia-carstairs&lt;br /&gt;' rel='nofollow noopener'>Lia!</a></i><br/><br/><i>
  <b>“To live was to be a fragment of the cosmere that was experiencing itself.”</b>
</i><br/><br/>**Do not read if you haven&apos;t read <i>The way of kings</i> yet**<br/><br/><i>
  <b>Words of Radiance</b>
</i> takes off soon after the events of The Way of Kings. Instead of dying like many had expected, Kaladin Stormblessed has become the captain of the royal bodyguards of Alethkar. However not all is solved and while he must protect the king and his highprinces, Kaladin must also</span>
  <span id="freeText9753148720196838150" style="display:none">*.·:·.☽✧ <b>5 stars</b> ✧☾.·:·.*<br /><br /><i>~Buddy-read with my favourite demon AKA <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/75966379-lia-carstairs&lt;br /&gt;" rel="nofollow noopener">Lia!</a></i><br /><br /><i>
  <b>“To live was to be a fragment of the cosmere that was experiencing itself.”</b>
</i><br /><br />**Do not read if you haven't read <i>The way of kings</i> yet**<br /><br /><i>
  <b>Words of Radiance</b>
</i> takes off soon after the events of The Way of Kings. Instead of dying like many had expected, Kaladin Stormblessed has become the captain of the royal bodyguards of Alethkar. However not all is solved and while he must protect the king and his highprinces, Kaladin must also deal with the mysterious and dangerous powers he finds himself having, that are somehow connected to Syl, his honorspren. <br /><br />By the command of his latest master, Szeth, the truthless assassin is still killing the most important men of Roshar, never getting caught, never getting killed. His latest task is to kill Dalinar Kholin -a powerful highprince known for his loyalty to the throne- and though he knows it will be a difficult thing to do, Szeth has no choice but to follow the will of his master, and put his life at stake once more to do what he must. <br /><br />After the thrilling and frightening events of the last book, Shallan is back on her feet, yet now, she knows dangerous information about the legendary Voidbringers and she must find a way to prevent them from returning. To do this, she must venture to the Shattered Plains, a journey that proves harder and harsher than she ever imagined and if she doesn’t get there soon enough, the civilization will fall apart and throw the entire world of Roshar into chaos. <i>
  <b>Words of Radiance</b>
</i> is a dark and thrilling sequel that dives deeper into Roshar and it’s secretive past, it explores loyalty, death and most importantly, power.<br /><br /><i>
  <b>“Expectation. That is the true soul of art. If you can give a man more than he expects, then he will laud you his entire life. If you can create an air of anticipation and feed it properly, you will succeed.”</b>
</i><br /><br />After I finished <i>The Way of Kings</i>, I thought it would be the best book in the series because it was just so amazing but somehow, <i>Words of Radiance</i> beat it, by a lot. Going into this, I had very high expectations and it’s safe to say that this book went above and beyond every single one of them. I don’t think I’ve ever read this many pages this fast. I read the entire book -just over 1000 pages- in a day and though it took up all my time, I have absolutely no regrets. Every single aspect of this book was done so well, I don’t have a single complaint. To put it simply, I absolutely adored <i>
  <b>Words of Radiance</b>
</i> and that is all. <br /><br /><i>
  <b>“As I fear not a child with a weapon he cannot lift, I will never fear the mind of a man who does not think.”</b>
</i><br /><br />A big section of my review for <i>The Way of Kings</i> was about the writing so instead of writing an entirely different one for this one, I’m just going to share the things I said in my other review. <br /><br /><i>“The writing was beautiful and fit so well with the atmosphere and themes of the book. I have read other books by Sanderson but most of them were “modern” fantasy and though the writing was good in those, the writing in this book (as a historical fantasy novel) was absolutely amazing and done so, so well. I’ve always been a sucker for third-person and this book has just increased my love for it. The third-person is written so well and in such a way that it allows readers to connect with the characters but to also fall in love with the setting and the fantastical world. This was 1000 pages of top-tier fantasy, it had complex world-building and the setting was detailed to the point where I felt like I was there, in Koshar. Despite the length of the novel. I was never bored because even in moments where the plot was slow, the writing was just so lush, I couldn't put the book down.”</i><br /><br />These are all the things I said and every single one of them still stand and apply to this book as well as the first. <br /><br /><i>
  <b>“For glory lit, and life alive, for goals unreached and aims to strive. All men must try, the wind did see. It is the test, it is the dream.”</b>
</i><br /><br /><b>Though the plot for the first book was fantastic, the way it is done in this book was so much better than the first.</b> The multiple perspectives allowed for a very engaging, fast-paced plot that left me flipping pages and reading at an almost inhuman speed. I really enjoyed the interludes throughout the book because though they pulled my attention away from the main storyline, they connected to the overall picture in a genius way. There were so many plot twists scattered throughout the book and the way they were foreshadowed left me mesmerized and amazed. The ending of the book was unlike anything I have ever read, it was absolutely amazing and the buildup was so, so good, my mind is still a little blown and I suspect it will be for a while.<br /><br /><b>The characters oh my god, the characters! I raved about them in my first review but because there is no such thing as enough raving, I will do it again here.</b><br /><br /><b>Kaladin</b> is possibly one of my favorite characters, ever. He’s such a layered, interesting character with a conflicted mind and a broken heart and though he struggles a lot through the book, his overall arc was such a beautiful thing to see. I said this before but I will say it again, the mental health representation we see in kaladin is some of the best I have ever seen. I find that often in fantasy, mental health issues are not very looked at, especially in historical fantasy and it frustrated me because though people probably didn’t talk about them, mental health issues definitely existed. I love Sanderson’s books so much because he isn’t afraid to show it all and he takes care to explore the topic and it’s obvious that he put care into creating Kaladin’s character and it made me love this book that much more. <br /><br /><i>
  <b>“I will protect even those I hate,” Kaladin whispered through bloody lips. “So long as it is right.”</b>
</i><br /><br /><b>Shallan</b> is an interesting character but I have a love/hate relationship with her. She is a genius and I love how determined she is but sometimes,the comments she makes frustrate me to no end, though I understand that’s exactly the point. I liked her relationship with that character but I’m not entirely feeling it yet so I guess I’ll wait and see. I really did like her dynamic with the other characters overall and I like how as the books progressed, she got much stronger and the Shallan from the beginning of The Way of Kings is very different from the Shallan at the end of this book, in the best way possible. <br /><br /><i>
  <b>“I can see what you’re up to.”<br />“Five foot six inches,” Shallan said. “I suspect that’s all I will ever be up to, unfortunately.”</b>
</i><br /><br /><i>
  <b>“I seek the truth,” Shallan said. “Wherever it may be, whoever may hold it. That’s who I am.”</b>
</i><br /><br /><b>Adolin</b> and <b>Dalinar</b> were also great characters and though we didn’t get much from their perspectives in this book, I enjoyed every chapter and I really liked their relationship and how much they have grown overtime, both individually and together. I can’t talk much about the other secondary characters without revealing spoilers but I really liked how interesting and morally grey they all were and I look forward to reading more from them in the next book(s). <br /><br />Overall, I loved this book with all my heart. I love Brandon Sanderson’s writing, I loved how interesting and engaging the plot was and I loved all the characters, despite all their flaws. I am simultaneously excited and terrified to read the next book but I can’t wait to see where the story goes!<br /><br /><i>
  <b>“All stories told have been told before. We tell them to ourselves, as did all men who ever were. And all men who ever will be. The only things new are the names.”</b>
</i><br /><br /><a href="https://mashlovesbooks.wordpress.com/2021/05/05/words-of-radiance-review/&lt;br /&gt;" rel="nofollow noopener">Blog Review</a><br /><br />Socials: <a href="https://mashlovesbooks.wordpress.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Blog</a> | <a href="https://www.pinterest.ca/Mashlovesbooks/_created/" rel="nofollow noopener">Pinterest</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="9753148720196838150" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


